-- Allot Communications, TripAdvisor: U.S. Equity Movers
-- B y   K a t i a   P o r z e c a n s k i
-- 2011-12-23T21:54:46Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-12-23/allot-communications-tripadvisor-u-s-equity-movers-correct-.html
(Corrects description of share repurchase in Flextronics
item in column that ran earlier.)  Shares of the following companies
are having unusual moves in U.S. trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of 1:45 p.m. in  New York .  Allot Communications Ltd. (ALLT)   fell 6.3 percent to
$15.65 after sinking 13 percent earlier, the biggest intraday
decline since Aug. 18. Bloomberg News reported that the Israeli
company sold its Internet-monitoring gear to technology
distributor RanTek A/S, which repackaged it and shipped it to
Iran. Israel prohibits trading with Iran. The company said it
complies with applicable laws and regulations and is
investigating the claims in the article.  Chico’s FAS Inc. (CHS)   rose 5.1 percent to $11.08, the
biggest gain in the  Russell 1000 . The women’s clothing retailer
is trading “extremely cheaply,” making it a target for private
equity investors, DealReporter said, citing an industry banker
it didn’t name. Chico’s didn’t return DealReporter’s calls.  Eastman Kodak Co. (EK)   gained 9.3 percent to 69 cents
after rising 19 percent earlier for the biggest intraday gain
since Oct. 6. The unprofitable 131-year-old imaging company said
its board elected Laura Quatela as a second president beginning
next year to serve alongside Philip Faraci.  Flextronics International Ltd. (FLEX)   rose 2.2 percent
to $5.95 after rising to $6 earlier, the highest intraday price
since Dec. 13. The supplier of cameras and battery chargers for
 Apple Inc. (AAPL)   said its board authorized an additional
share repurchase plan that increases the buyback authorization
to 43 million shares.  Rambus Inc. (RMBS)   rose 14 percent to $8.36, the second-
biggest gain in the  Russell 2000 . The designer of high-speed
memory chips said it settled patent disputes with  Broadcom Corp. (BRCM) 
 and signed a five-year licensing agreement.  Shutterfly Inc. (SFLY)   dropped 9.3 percent to $22.76
after falling 10 percent, the most intraday since Nov. 30. The
Internet-based photo storage and printing company forecast
fourth-quarter net revenue of no more than $264 million, lower
than the earlier estimate of at least $270.5 million.  SunPower Corp.  (SPWR US) gained 2.9 percent to $6.02 after
jumping 19.5 percent earlier, the biggest intraday since April
29.  Total SA (FP)   said it boosted its stake in the solar
manufacturer to 66 percent by selling SunPower a stake in
Tenesol SA, which makes solar panels.  TripAdvisor Inc.  (TRIP US) rose 3.6 percent, the biggest
gain on the Standard and Poor’s 500 Index, to $25.42. The
world’s largest travel site, was rated “neutral” in new
coverage at UBS AG, with a price estimate of $27.  United Continental Holdings Inc. (UAL)   dropped 5.2
percent to $19.21 after falling 9.2 percent earlier, the biggest
intraday decline since Oct. 3. The airline holding company
estimated fourth-quarter domestic capacity would decrease 4.8
percent.  Yanzhou Coal Mining Co. (YZC)   jumped 6.4 percent, the
biggest intraday gain since Nov. 2, to $21.31. China’s fourth-
biggest coal producer agreed to buy Sydney, Australia-based
Gloucester Coal Ltd. (GCL AU) for about A$2.1 billion ($2.1
billion) in cash and shares.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Katia Porzecanski in New York at 
 kporzecansk1@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
